				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1259135&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205357" alt="Hornby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1259135)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;" >Hornby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1336005052 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 May 2012 00:30</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1435913">
									

<blockquote>
<p>I guess I'm just hesitant about this being labelled as a guide when it's really just one interpretation of Foundation structure.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This. While there is no canon, guides imply something as being part of the general there-is-no-canon which is referenced within the site. Things like D-Class being terminated at the end of the month, or the security clearance levels, or the MTF and Secure Locations, or even something as fundamental as Keter/Euclid/Safe/Neutralized/Explained.</p>
<p>I suppose I wouldn't have an objection to something like this page existing in the abstract, but I'd hope it would be the result of the existing works on the site. For example, Agent Lombardi (and plenty of others) mention &quot;Acquisitions&quot;. (Which isn't on this list.) While the means by which SCPs are acquired are as diverse as the list itself, there seems to be some nebulous consensus (by at least some of the authors on this site; I make no claims on this being a majority viewpoint) on the wiki that &quot;Acquisitions&quot; is a different part of the Foundation than the MTFs.</p>
<p>I see this being something which is on the same level as &quot;XK-class scenarios&quot; or &quot;Class-A/B/(whatever) amnesiacs&quot;, where there isn't a standardized definition and is left up to the author for any particular article. Apart from the existence of O5 Command and the existence of Mobile Task Forces, I think it may be best that the Foundation's structure simply be left to be whatever is most useful for a particular author.</p>

							</div>

								
					
