					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/echofourdelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(515520); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=515520&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205357" alt="EchoFourDelta" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=515520)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/echofourdelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(515520); return false;" >EchoFourDelta</a></span> <span class="odate time_1335989992 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 May 2012 20:19</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1435594">
									

<p>Generally, you're looking at 12-16 individuals on the extreme low end of something like that. Either a squad, or a squad-reinforced. You have to consider what the MTF is used for. If it's a simple pickup, a random-ass field agent is gonna drive up in a van, and Ocean's 11 away with it on his own or with another agent or so. Mobile Task Forces are gonna be a step up from that, where the Foundation would be expecting an ordeal in retrieval, or would need more manpower, or where an overt display of force would either be unnoticed or looked over.</p>
<p>That said, a general-purpose unit might include 40-45 individuals, and that's including nothing but operating forces. Larger groups might be composed of around 100-120 individuals, before support staff are included. And I'm talking special forces type shit here. The current idea of MTF matches up pretty well with Movie Task Force.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p>Military Consultant, SCP Wiki</p>

				</div>
					
					
